To achieve the effect of changing an iframe's width based on different screen widths, you can use CSS media queries for styling and JavaScript for more dynamic adjustments if needed. However, for this example, CSS will suffice for simplicity and efficiency.

Below is an example that includes HTML, CSS, and a brief JavaScript snippet (though the JavaScript part is optional and provided for educational purposes on how to dynamically adjust the iframe width using JavaScript).

### HTML

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Responsive Iframe</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <iframe src="https://example.com" frameborder="0" id="responsiveIframe"></iframe>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (in style.css file)

```css
/* Default width for iframe */
#iframe-container {
    width: 100%;
}

#iframe-container iframe {
    width: 100%;
    height: 500px; /* Example height */
    border: none;
}

/* Media queries to adjust iframe width based on viewport width */
@media (max-width: 360px) {
    #iframe-container iframe {
        width: 100%; /* Full width on small screens */
    }
}

@media (min-width: 361px) and (max-width: 720px) {
    #iframe-container iframe {
        width: 80%; /* 80% width on medium screens */
        margin: 0 auto; /* Center the iframe */
    }
}

@media (min-width: 721px) and (max-width: 1400px) {
    #iframe-container iframe {
        width: 70%; /* 70% width on larger screens */
        margin: 0 auto; /* Center the iframe */
    }
}

@media (min-width: 1401px) {
    #iframe-container iframe {
        width: 60%; /* 60% width on extra large screens */
        margin: 0 auto; /* Center the iframe */
    }
}
```

However, I realized I made an incorrect assumption about your HTML structure. Since you didn't specify an `id` for your iframe or a container, let's adjust the CSS to directly target the iframe without needing a container or an ID, and correct the media queries to directly apply to the iframe:

```css
iframe {
    width: 100%;
    height: 500px; /* Example height */
    border: none;
}

/* Media queries to adjust iframe width based on viewport width */
@media (max-width: 360px) {
