Below is an example code that demonstrates how to adjust the width of an iframe based on different screen widths (viewport) using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. The widths we'll target are 360px, 720px, and 1400px.

### HTML

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Responsive Iframe</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>

<iframe id="responsiveIframe" src="https://example.com" frameborder="0" width="100%" height="500"></iframe>

<script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### CSS (in style.css file)

```css
/* Basic styling for the iframe */
#iframe-container {
    width: 100%;
    height: 500px;
    margin: 20px auto;
}

#iframe-container iframe {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
    border: none;
}
```

### JavaScript (in script.js file)

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    const iframe = document.getElementById('responsiveIframe');
    const viewportWidth = window.innerWidth || document.documentElement.clientWidth || document.body.clientWidth;

    function adjustIframeWidth() {
        const currentWidth = window.innerWidth || document.documentElement.clientWidth || document.body.clientWidth;

        if (currentWidth <= 360) {
            iframe.style.width = '300px'; // Adjusted width for screens up to 360px
        } else if (currentWidth <= 720) {
            iframe.style.width = '600px'; // Adjusted width for screens up to 720px
        } else if (currentWidth <= 1400) {
            iframe.style.width = '1000px'; // Adjusted width for screens up to 1400px
        } else {
            iframe.style.width = '1200px'; // Default width for screens larger than 1400px
        }
    }

    // Initial adjustment
    adjustIframeWidth();

    // Adjust on window resize
    window.addEventListener('resize', function() {
        adjustIframeWidth();
    });
});
```

This code snippet does the following:
- The HTML sets up a basic page with an iframe.
- The CSS adds basic styling to ensure the iframe is responsive.
- The JavaScript code checks the current viewport width and adjusts the iframe's width accordingly. It also listens for the window's resize event to adjust the iframe's width dynamically as the user resizes the browser window.

Please note, you might need to adjust the widths in the JavaScript code to better fit your specific use case, especially considering the content of the iframe and how it should be displayed across different screen sizes.

