To achieve the desired behavior where the navigation hides on scroll down and shows on scroll up with a sliding animation, and to disable this animation for pages that don't scroll (or have minimal scrolling), you can use JavaScript along with CSS for the animation. The approach involves tracking the scroll direction and applying a class to the navigation element based on the scroll direction. For disabling the animation on pages with minimal or no scrolling, you can check the scroll height of the document.

Here's a basic example of how you could implement this:

### HTML

```html
<nav id="nav" class="nav">
  <!-- Your navigation content here -->
</nav>
```

### CSS

```css
.nav {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  width: 100%;
  background-color: #333;
  color: #fff;
  padding: 1em;
  text-align: center;
  transition: transform 0.3s ease-in-out;
}

.nav-hide {
  transform: translateY(-100%);
}

/* Optional: For better understanding, you can add this to see the effect more clearly */
body {
  margin: 0;
  height: 200vh; /* Just for demonstration, to have a scrollable page */
  background-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, #f7f7f7, #fff);
}
```

### JavaScript

```javascript
const nav = document.getElementById('nav');
let lastScrollY = window.scrollY;
let slack = 100; // Adjust this value based on your needs
let ticking = false;

function onScroll() {
  if (!ticking) {
    requestAnimationFrame(function() {
      const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

      // Check if we need to show or hide the nav
      if (currentScrollY > lastScrollY) {
        // Scrolling down
        nav.classList.add('nav-hide');
      } else if (currentScrollY < lastScrollY && currentScrollY + window.innerHeight < document.body.offsetHeight - slack) {
        // Scrolling up and not at the very top
        nav.classList.remove('nav-hide');
      }

      // If we are at the top of the page or the page doesn't scroll much, remove the hide class
      if (currentScrollY === 0 || document.body.offsetHeight - window.innerHeight <= slack) {
        nav.classList.remove('nav-hide');
      }

      lastScrollY = currentScrollY;
      ticking = false;
    });
    ticking = true;
  }
}

window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll);
```

This code snippet does the following:
- It listens for the scroll event on the window.
- When a scroll event occurs, it checks the current scroll position (`window.scrollY`) and compares it with the last known scroll position (`lastScrollY`).
- Based on the comparison, it decides whether to add or remove the `nav-hide` class from the navigation element, effectively hiding or showing it.
- The `slack` variable is used to determine if the page scrolls enough to warrant hiding the navigation. If the page's content height minus the viewport height is less than or equal to the `slack` value, the navigation remains visible.
- The `requestAnimationFrame` function is used to ensure that the scroll event handling is done efficiently, preventing excessive function calls during scrolling.

You can adjust the `slack` value based on your specific requirements to fine-tune when the navigation should be hidden or shown based on the scroll position and the page's scrollability.

